Templars are divine warrior-healers who synthesize Paladin advance doctrine with Priest restoration capability, descending from the Solar Court's temple-guard auxiliaries who stood at the threshold between battle-clergy and ceremonial ministry. The synthesis was forced during the garrison crisis of the Violet Compact's founding years, when a combined Paladin-Priest force securing former Conclave-adjacent territories found itself too few to maintain separate advance-post and interior functions. Practitioners who began training across doctrinal lines discovered that integration at depth produced qualitatively different results from minimum-coverage cross-training: a Paladin with genuine Priest healing competence could maintain offensive pressure while simultaneously supporting allies in ways neither doctrine separately accommodated; a Priest with genuine Paladin combat competence could conduct healing operations in active threat environments that would otherwise require Paladin escort to secure. The revived Solar Court title of Templar designated practitioners who achieved genuine depth in both functions. The Enhanced Heal technique — the tradition's most technically sophisticated contribution — integrates healing channel work with status-cure functions (cure blindness, remove curse, cure poison) as simultaneous subsidiary channels rather than sequential separate applications, eliminating the treatment gap during which active poisons continue damage. The Violet Compact eventually absorbed the garrison-crisis force as the sanctioned Templar Corps, a formal order operating across all five cities with dual civic and religious authority — when the two diverge, Solar Court auxiliary doctrine (oath-bound to sacred spaces rather than to commanders) provides the resolution: the oath governs. The Templar tradition holds that Paladin advance-and-sanctify and Priest sustain-and-restore are one function requiring a practitioner who shifts between them as conditions require, not two functions requiring two specialists.

